{"serial": "41052", "department_serial": 40, "code": "BA8066", "class": "*", "name": {"en": "The Overview for IT Industries", "ch": "電子與資訊產業概論"}, "notice": {"en": "", "ch": ""}, "instructor": {"en": ["Chen, Shiuann-Shuoh"], "ch": ["陳炫碩"]}, "credits": 3, "time_loc": [{"time": {"week": 2, "session": ["A", "B", "C"]}, "loc": {"building": "I1", "room": "018"}}], "isRequired": false, "isFullSem": false, "MaxStu": 70, "department": {"ch": "企業管理學系", "en": "Department of Business Administration"}, "system": {"ch": "碩博同修", "en": "Master/Doctoral Programme"}, "language": {"ch": "國語", "en": "Chinese"}, "card": {"ch": "部份使用", "en": "Optional"}, "assigned": 9, "selected": 66, "remark": {"ch": "", "en": ""}, "goal": {"ch": "依老師上課說明", "en": "“IT industry has been one of the major forces of economy growth in Taiwan for the past 20 years.  Most courses in Business School have been function-oriented with emphases on activities and tasks performed by a particular functional department in a company.  Little attention has been given to the analysis of a single industry.  This course attempts to address the characters of IT industry and their significance on the competitive advantage of companies in this industry.  The topics to be covered are the followings.\n‧ The theory of disruptive innovation and its impacts on competition.\n‧ Technology Adoption Life Cycle (crossing the chasm, inside the tornado)\n‧ Platform Competition\n‧ Digital Convergence“"}, "outline": {"ch": "依老師上課說明", "en": "“Classes will be mainly conducted in the form of lecture, given that students are not familiar with the topics covered in this course.  In each class session, a half of an hour will be devoted to the discussion of news in IT industry for the past week.  As the course progresses toward the end the semester, the portion of case discussion will gradually increase.  Students are expected to learn the nature of IT industry competition from management perspectives.\nAssignment\nBusiness cases for different topics will be discussed.  Students as a team are asked to prepare each case.  The case discussion will be conducted in an interactive way by randomly assigning students to present their homework and host discussions in class.\nTeam work is strongly encouraged in this class.  Students are required to work in a group for their homework throughout the semester.  Peer review will be taken as a significant portion of member’s efforts and contributions to each team project.     Class participation will represent another significant portion of students’ final grade.\nPlagiarism and Academic Honesty:\nAll materials from any source (including website) other than yourself must be properly cited.  Under no circumstance, can students plagiarize any assignment in any form.  The NCU policy on the honor code applies to this course.\n1 (09/19) Disruptive innovation\n2 (09/26) Value networks and the impetus to innovate\n3 (10/03) How can we beat our most powerful competitors\n4 (10/10) What products would customers want to buy\n5 (10/17) What are the best customers for our products\n6 (10/24) Getting the scope of business right\n7 (10/31) How to avoid commodilization\n8 (11/07) Mid-term exam\n9 (11/14) The experience economy\n10 (11/21) Blue ocean strategy\n11 (11/28) The Delta project\n12 (12/05) High-tech marketing enlightenment\n13 (12/12) D-Day analogy\n14 (12/19) Target the point of attack\n15 (12/26) Assemble the invasion forces\n16 (01/02) Defining the battle\n17 (01/09) Lunch the invasion\n18 (01/16) Final exam“"}, "textbook": {"ch": "依老師上課說明", "en": "“‧ G. Moore, “Inside the Tornado”, Harper Business, 1995.\n‧ G. Moore, “Dealing with Darwin”, Harper Business, 2005.\n‧ C. Markides ＆ P. Geroski, “Fast Second”, Jossey-Bass, 2004.\n‧ G. Tellis ＆ P. Golder, “Will ＆ Vision”, McGraw-Hill, 2002.\n‧ A. Gawer ＆ M. Cusumano, “Platform Leadership”, HBS Press, 2002.\n‧ A. Hax, D. Wilde, L. Thurow, “The Delta Project”, Palgrave Macmillan, 2001.\n‧ T. Kelly, J. Littman, “The Ten Faces of Innovation”, Currency, 2005.\n‧ T. Kelly, “The Art of Innovation”, Currency, 2001.\n‧ “Competing in the age of Digital Convergence”, edited by D. Yoffie, HBS Press, 1997.\n‧ J. Utterback, “Mastering of the Dynamics of Innovation”, HBS Press, 1994.\n‧ C. Christensen, “The Innovator’s Dilemma”, HBS Press, 1997.\n‧ C. Christensen, “The Innovator’s Solution”, HBS Press, 2003.\n‧ C. Christensen, “Seeing What’s Next”, HBS Press, 2004.\n‧ G. Moore, “Crossing the Chasm”, Harper Business, 1991 (1999).“"}, "selfCompiledRate": {"ch": "0", "en": "0"}, "instructMethod": {"ch": "講授\n研討", "en": ["Lecture", "Seminar"]}, "gradMethod": {"ch": "Case Presentation (Group): 30％\nSelf Evaluation: 30％\nParticipation in Discussion: 40％", "en": "Case Presentation (Group): 30％\nSelf Evaluation: 30％\nParticipation in Discussion: 40％"}, "officeHour": {"ch": "星期二/09:00-17:00 星期五/09:00-12:00", "en": "\"Tuesday 9:00-17:00\nFriday 9:00-12:00\n\""}, "teachWeeks": {"ch": "18", "en": "18"}, "flexDiscription": {"ch": "", "en": ""}, "domain": {"ch": "企業資源規劃", "en": "企業資源規劃"}, "map": {"ch": [{"competencies": "原創性", "rating": "(5)非常高", "assesments": ["口頭報告/口試", "出席/課堂表現", "自我評量/同儕互評"]}, {"competencies": "熟悉其專業領域文獻", "rating": "(3)普通", "assesments": ["口頭報告/口試", "出席/課堂表現", "自我評量/同儕互評"]}, {"competencies": "獨立思考和解決問題能力", "rating": "(5)非常高", "assesments": ["口頭報告/口試", "出席/課堂表現", "自我評量/同儕互評"]}, {"competencies": "溝通能力", "rating": "(5)非常高", "assesments": ["口頭報告/口試", "出席/課堂表現", "自我評量/同儕互評"]}], "en": [{"competencies": "Original Contribution", "rating": "(5)VeryHigh", "assesments": ["Presentation/Oral Exam", "Attendance/Performance", "Self Assessment/ Peer Assessment"]}, {"competencies": "Proficiency with Discipline-related Literature", "rating": "(3)Medium", "assesments": ["Presentation/Oral Exam", "Attendance/Performance", "Self Assessment/ Peer Assessment"]}, {"competencies": "Critical Thinking and Problem-solving", "rating": "(5)VeryHigh", "assesments": ["Presentation/Oral Exam", "Attendance/Performance", "Self Ass